@wildwood2000: 
"two (US officials)  ...  One decision that has been made, they said, speaking on the condition of anonymity, is to avoid any moves that exceed the Russian election hacking and risk an escalating cyber conflict that could spiral out of control."
http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-russia-cyber-idUSKBN14H1SR

I would think sanctions would require:  (1) direct economic/physical damage can be identified by a cyber incident; 
(2) a specific actor can be reliably or probably tied to the damage (attribution); 
(3) the actor engages in friendly economic activity with the victim (e.g. ISIS sanctions aren't going to be because of its cyber efforts--they're being sanctioned because they're jerks) ; and 
(4) sanctions are not likely to escalate into further, more damaging actions.  (Yes there are a lot of assumptions in that list) These conditions make sanctions an unlikely tool  against cyber attacks and espionage but given the volume of cyber incidents, and the increasing magnitude of cyber incidents (think OPM, Target, Home Depot, Sony), it's highly conceivable these conditions could be met in at least one incident in the near-term (12 months).
